article.description:
Latrell Sprewell scored 13 of his 33 points
in the third quarter and the New York Knicks snapped a seven-game
road losing skid by defeating the Orlando Magic 111-102 Friday
night.
article.headline: Knicks stop seven-game road losing streak
article.linkText: Sprewell's scoring surge helps Knicks end road skid
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- The Orlando Magic are managing to defeat every team they come across recently -- except the New York Knicks.
 
Sprewell
Latrell Sprewell scored 13 of his 33 points in the third quarter and New York beat Orlando for the second time in a week, 111-102 Friday night. Those are the Magic's only losses in their last nine games. "I'm going to cherish this feeling right here," New York coach Don Chaney said. Allan Houston added 25 points and a season-high nine rebounds, while Shandon Anderson came off the bench to score 20. The Knicks shot 52.7 percent to snap a seven-game road losing skid. New York used a small lineup, as it had in the double-overtime win a week ago, with the 6-foot-6 Anderson a crucial component. At one point, he was matched against 6-foot-10 Shawn Kemp but still got the defensive stop. "His quickness versus their bigs inside worked out well," Chaney said. "It made them change their lineup." Added Sprewell: "We have to make up for the lack of size with effort and hard work, and I thought we did it." For Orlando, Tracy McGrady scored 37 points _ 14 in second quarter. Drew Gooden had 19 points and eight rebounds, falling shy of his seventh double-double in eight games since being acquired from Memphis in a trade. Sprewell's 3-pointer with 6:14 left to play gave New York a 97-84 lead, its largest of the game. He shot 12-for-20 from the field and made all seven of his foul shots. In the Knicks' double-overtime win against Orlando last week, he had 28 points -- 18 after regulation. "I've been fortunate to be able to knock down shots for us the last couple of games against them," Sprewell said. "It's all about stepping up and making plays." Orlando closed within five points with 59 seconds remaining on a dunk by Gordan Giricek, who finished with 18 points. But New York sank four free throws in the final 40 seconds to seal the win and snap Orlando's five-game home win streak. "I thought we showed up -- and they showed up for a playoff game," Orlando coach Doc Rivers said. "For a young team, that's a great lesson. I thought their intensity throughout the night was notch above ours." In the third quarter, the Knicks scored 34 points on 11-for-18 shooting. They closed the period on a 20-5 run for an eight-point advantage. New York went on a 17-3 run late in the first quarter to go ahead by double digits. Houston had seven points, and his two free throws put the Knicks up 26-15 with two minutes remaining in the quarter. But two heady backcourt defensive plays by Darrell Armstrong sparked a furious Orlando rally, and the Magic took a nine-point lead with 1:14 left before halftime. In the 28-8 run, McGrady had 13 points. Orlando led 54-47 at the break. Game notes
McGrady has led (or tied) the Magic in scoring in 33 straight games. The last time someone other than McGrady had the honors was Dec. 18th, when Pat Garrity had 24 points at Utah. ... McGrady has scored 20-plus points 54 times and 30-plus points 36 times. ... Knicks point guard Charlie Ward was activated from the injured list before the game. He had missed the previous eight games with an abdominal strain. Ward was scoreless in four minutes. To make room on the roster for Ward's return, New York placed Lavor Postell on the injured list due to tendinitis in his left knee. ... The game was a sellout, Orlando's fourth.
